This is Bill Vernon and David Carson. Joan Slonczewski is a young biochemist who
practices as a scientist and writes science fiction. She brings into her writing

00:54.260 --> 01:03.520
another element from her life. She is a practicing Quaker. Slonczewski's first
novel bears the title Still Forms on Foxfield. We asked her to explain the origin

01:03.520 --> 01:14.500
of the title. Foxfield is the name of the planet that was named after the Quaker
settled the planet and they named it after George Fox who was the founder of the

01:14.500 --> 01:25.980
Quaker religion. "Still forms" is a phrase that comes from a poem by Whittier. John
Greenleaf Whittier who was a Quaker and he would he wrote a poem which described

01:25.980 --> 01:38.660
the experience of being in a Quaker meeting and he spoke of the still forms on
either side that somehow breathed a special light and the still forms refers to

01:38.660 --> 01:48.560
the still forms of the people who were around him in the Quaker meeting. From the
title and packaging of this novel the prospective reader might assume it is

01:48.560 --> 01:57.660
strictly a soft science book. On the contrary the novel has a good deal of hard
science woven in with good characterization. Slonczewski's aliens the Commensals

01:57.660 --> 02:06.000
are well drawn they are sentient mobile plants that communicate by emitting and
detecting volatile chemicals. We discover that Slonczewski came up with these

02:06.000 --> 02:17.360
aliens while in the laboratory. Listen to her describe her thoughts. In my
scientific work I've studied chemical communication among bacteria and it was

02:17.360 --> 02:28.460
sort of of interest to me supposing you could have an an alien intelligence that
would communicate chemically uh through through things like pheromones almost um

02:28.460 --> 02:41.580
how would this work? would it be possible? And I tried to think what kind of of
creatures these might be and and how they might work in different ways than our

02:41.580 --> 02:56.980
usual vertebrates, mammals, humans, and so on, and so it occurred to me they might
have developed from plants for for instance. Uh they they might use something

02:56.980 --> 03:06.880
akin to plant hormones. Before Slonczewski could write Still Forms on Foxfield she
had to find a way to incorporate these aliens with the Quakers who were to be

03:06.880 --> 03:21.600
the human characters. And I also was getting much interested in into into into
Quakerism I guess at a slightly later date and the two things finally meshed

03:21.600 --> 03:33.360
together and that was really the key to to the book was when I was able to
combine those two ideas the idea of the aliens and the Quakers and how they

03:33.360 --> 03:43.040
would interact and at that point that's when it became possible to move ahead
with the book. It seems unbelievable at first that science and Quakerism can mix

03:43.040 --> 03:56.520
so easily. Here Slonczewski explains a bit about Quakerism and how for her the
combination works the religion is basically christian it developed from um

03:56.520 --> 04:08.700
during the Protestant Reformation it was one of the Protestant branches but at
the same time it has become very universal as it has developed and Quakers today

04:08.700 --> 04:21.900
see a great affinity with other somewhat universalist religions such as Buddhism
for example and I made that parallel in my book also. And it is also a religion

04:21.900 --> 04:33.980
which scientists often find congenial because of the emphasis on the experience
of the individual in science you you test the universe by making experiments. Uh

04:33.980 --> 04:49.260
Quakers test the spiritual universe by meditation and and an inward seeking of
truth an almost an inward type of experiment. Join us next time when we continue

04:49.260 --> 04:51.540
our talk with author Joan Slonczewski.

