06:37.360 --> 06:39.660
We are continuing our series on science fiction author,

6:39.820 --> 06:40.780
Joan Slonczewski.

06:41.060 --> 06:45.560
Slonczewski carries the credentials of being a practicing scientist and a devout Quaker.

06:45.560 --> 06:50.640
She is uniquely qualified to comment on the treatments of science and religion in science fiction.

06:51.020 --> 06:54.540
We asked her her view on the presentation of religion in science fiction.

06:55.520 --> 06:58.100
I'm disappointed that it hasn't been treated more.

06:58.960 --> 07:05.780
I think that it has been, where it has been treated, it's often been treated very well.

07:06.220 --> 07:11.460
Heinlein's Stranger in a Strange Land is a very controversial treatment of it, but

07:12.300 --> 07:18.080
in a way it made people think about the issues and that was good.

07:19.640 --> 07:21.940
What disappoints me more is that

07:23.860 --> 07:29.740
often writers seem to create universes in which religion does not exist at all.

07:30.420 --> 07:34.600
You see, I think you don't necessarily have to write a book about religion,

07:35.160 --> 07:41.780
but it seems almost dishonest to write about a world where it doesn't exist because it's such a

07:41.780 --> 07:47.420
prevalent part of life. And often it's prevalent in ways that you simply don't realize.

07:47.940 --> 07:53.760
For example, I'm a scientist, my father is a scientist, and yet when I was little I learned

07:53.760 --> 07:59.700
about Adam and Eve before I learned about evolution simply because it's such a basic

07:59.700 --> 08:07.780
part of the culture. And a lot of us often don't realize how basic it is and how we revert to it

08:08.540 --> 08:23.500
in a crisis, such as a death in the family, things like that. And in
science fiction, very often people are portrayed in the far future with the idea

08:23.500 --> 08:35.680
that simply religion has died out and there's no more need for it anymore.
Whereas I find that to be an unrealistic portrayal. It seems to me that there

08:35.680 --> 08:51.480
always will be people who will need religion, that it's a basic part of the
human experience and that science is never going to completely replace that for

08:51.480 --> 09:02.140
people. Slonczewski has read a great deal of science fiction. We asked her what
she watches out for when she reads a book featuring scientists at work. What I

09:02.140 --> 09:13.560
have my eye on really is the interaction between science and people. And that's
the one thing that I think is the sign of an outstanding writer, is the one who

09:13.560 --> 09:27.400
can really show how science operates in real life, not how we would like it to
operate in a fantasy life. I think Heinlein is, of course, the ideal example of

09:27.400 --> 09:45.060
that. In most of the good Heinlein stories, he will take a look at technology
and yet show the human perspectives on it and show how ordinary people's lives

09:45.060 --> 09:56.080
are affected. Since Slonczewski is a young writer just beginning her career, we
asked her what her advice is to aspiring writers. The most important thing in

09:56.080 --> 10:10.980
writing is to be distinctive. And by that I don't mean outrageous necessarily,
but to find whatever you have that is unique in your experience. And at every

10:10.980 --> 10:20.740
step of your writing, try to write something that hasn't been written before.
The second thing I would say is you just have to keep submitting what you write

10:20.740 --> 10:32.240
because... Now, I was very fortunate that the first publisher I sent my novel to
happened to have an editor who really liked the idea and was taken with it.

10:32.340 --> 10:33.760
That's an unusual thing.

10:36.320 --> 10:46.420
Agatha Christie took 11 tries to get her first book published. You know, and
there are all sorts of stories like that. So I would say those are the two main

10:46.420 --> 11:03.240
things. Try to be... To say the ordinary in a distinctive way. To write
originally. And whatever you write, just keep submitting it to publication. Joan

11:03.240 --> 11:07.440
Slonczewski, a young scientist with great promise as a science fiction writer.

